### SECTION 3: OPERATIONS & PRODUCTIVITY (Prompts 11–15)

**Prompt 11 — Meeting Summary into Action Items**

> Here are my notes from a meeting: [PASTE NOTES]. Organize these into: (1) a 3–5 sentence summary of what was discussed, (2) a clean action items list with owner and deadline for each item, (3) any open questions that need follow-up. Format it so I can copy and paste it directly into an email or Slack message.

**Prompt 12 — SOPs from a Process You Already Do**

> I want to document a standard operating procedure (SOP) for a task I do regularly. Here's how I currently do it: [DESCRIBE THE PROCESS]. Write this as a clear, step-by-step SOP that someone else could follow without asking me questions. Include: purpose, who this is for, tools or resources needed, step-by-step process, notes and exceptions, and what success looks like.

**Prompt 13 — Weekly Priority Planning**

> I want to plan my week. Here is my situation: [DESCRIBE YOUR GOALS FOR THE WEEK, CURRENT PROJECTS, AND ANY DEADLINES]. Help me create a weekly priority plan with: my top 3 must-do outcomes for the week, a day-by-day task list organized by priority, a note on what I should protect or delegate, and one risk or potential blocker to watch for.

**Prompt 14 — Summarize a Long Document**

> Here is a long document I need to understand quickly: [PASTE DOCUMENT OR DESCRIBE IT]. Give me: (1) a 3–5 sentence executive summary, (2) the 5 most important points, (3) anything that requires my direct decision or action, (4) any red flags or concerns I should know about. Format as a clean briefing I can read in under 2 minutes.

**Prompt 15 — Feedback on Your Own Writing**

> I've written the following: [PASTE YOUR WRITING]. Act as a professional editor. Give me honest feedback on: clarity (is the message obvious?), tone (does it match my intent?), structure (does it flow?), and impact (will it land with the reader?). Then give me a revised version that addresses the main issues. Be direct — I don't need praise, I need a better piece.

